    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-04-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-04-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="328"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d328">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> Files: Lot 59 D 237</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Director of the Office of United Nations
                        Political and Security Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Wainhouse</hi>) <hi
                        rend="italic">to the Assistant Secretary of State for United Nations
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HJD1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hickerson</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d328fn1">Memorandum directed also to Mr.
                            <persName corresp="#p_SDV1">Sandifer</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-04-30">April 30,
                            1951</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: Attached Draft Resolution.</p>
                <p>The attached draft resolution was sent on by <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> to
                    Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MEP1">Maffitt</persName>, <gloss target="#t_USUN1"
                        >USUN</gloss> presumably last Thursday.<note n="2" xml:id="d328fn2">April
                        26.</note> We first became aware of the existence of this draft this morning
                    when Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WDJ1">Worcester</persName> of <gloss
                        target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> handed copies to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BBG1"
                        >Bechhoefer</persName> and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LJW1">Ludlow</persName>
                    in anticipation of a 2 P M meeting in <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> on
                    it.</p>
                <p>In a conversation which Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LJW1">Ludlow</persName> had
                    with Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MEP1">Maffitt</persName> this morning, Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_LJW1">Ludlow</persName> learned that Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MEP1">Maffitt</persName> had been talking to the British and
                    French from this draft resolution. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LJW1"
                        >Ludlow</persName> told Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MEP1">Maffitt</persName>
                    that <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> had not seen this draft, nor did it
                    know of its existence, and suggested to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MEP1"
                        >Maffitt</persName> that he not discuss this draft any further. Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_LJW1">Ludlow</persName> stated that the Department’s
                    position is and remains that which was contained in <gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 845 to <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>, April 13.<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d328fn3">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_635">p. 635</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I telephoned Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KSKC1">Kopper</persName> and on learning
                    that he was out, talked to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SW1">Wells
                        Stabler</persName> who told me that this draft was sent on to Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MEP1">Maffitt</persName> because the latter was in need of
                    something with which to talk to the British and French; that <gloss
                        target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> had sought to clear this draft with officers in
                        <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> but was unable to reach those
                    officers!</p>
                <p>The draft in substance, you will note, is unacceptable to <gloss target="#t_UNP1"
                        >UNP</gloss> and is in excess of the Department’s position as set forth in
                        <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 845.</p>
                <p>I have requested Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BBG1">Bechhoefer</persName> and Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_LJW1">Ludlow</persName> to concert with <gloss
                        target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> on a draft which would be mutually acceptable to
                    both <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_UNA1"
                    >UNA</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WDW1">D[<hi rend="smallcaps">avid</hi>] W. W[<hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ainhouse</hi>]</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <pb facs="0692" n="652" xml:id="pg_652"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Attachment]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">Draft Resolution</hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#left">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        </seg>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">[<date
                                ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content"
                                calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1951-04-30T23:59:59-04:00"
                                notBefore="1951-04-26T00:00:00-04:00">undated</date>.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p rend="center">A.</p>
                    <p>1. The Security Council,</p>
                    <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                    <p>2. Decides that the deterioration of the situation in the Demilitarized Zone
                        provided for by Article 5 of the Israel–Syria Armistice Agreement of July
                        20, 1949, has resulted primarily from the refusal of the Israel Government
                        to comply with the requests of the Chief of Staff of the <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Truce Supervision Organization regarding the
                        engineering operations of the Palestine Land Development Company in the
                        Demilitarized Zone.</p>
                    <p>3. Considers that this attitude on the part of Israel has resulted in the
                        inability of the Mixed Armistice Commission to deal appropriately with the
                        situation in the Demilitarized Zone.</p>
                    <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                    <p rend="center">B.</p>
                    <p>1. The Security Council deplores the series of incidents which have occurred
                        in the Demilitarized Zone resulting in the loss of Israeli and Arab lives
                        and the bombing of Syrian soil by Israel military forces for which, it is
                        noted, apology has been made by the Israel representative on April 25,
                        1951.</p>
                    <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
